{"news_desk": "Foreign", "print_page": "1", "section_name": "World", "subsection_name": "Americas", "byline": {"contributor": "Paulina Villegas contributed reporting from El Calvario and Mexico City.", "original": "By AZAM AHMED", "person": [{"rank": 1, "role": "reported", "firstname": "Azam", "organization": "", "lastname": "AHMED"}]}, "abstract": "Increased demand for heroin in United States has prompted many Mexican farmers to switch crops to opium, and many young Mexicans are quitting school in favor of lucrative work picking poppies; many in small mountain villages of Guerrero State, known for drug cartel-related violence, are unaware of role they play in international drug trade.", "type_of_material": "News", "word_count": "1681", "lead_paragraph": "To meet the U.S. demand for heroin, Mexico is enlisting children to harvest opium. The money is too much to ignore for most, and the terrain is more manageable for those of slighter frame.", "pub_date": "2015-08-30T00:00:00Z", "document_type": "article", "slideshow_credits": null, "headline": {"main": "Young Hands in Mexico Feed Growing U.S. Demand for Heroin", "print_headline": "Young Hands in Mexico Feed Growing U.S. Demand for Heroin "}, "snippet": "To meet the U.S. demand for heroin, Mexico is enlisting children to harvest opium. The money is too much to ignore for most, and the terrain is more manageable for those of slighter frame.", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"widewidth": "190", "wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-thumbWide.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 190, "subtype": "wide"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400", "xlarge": "images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-articleLarge.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 600, "subtype": "xlarge"}, {"h